{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595239"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:01:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:01:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15341"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15341"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8032"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70077"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8032"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15341"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55540"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"582"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19514"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70077"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute variceal haemorrhage is a life-threatening complication of portal hypertension that requires urgent intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements correctly describes the treatment of acute variceal haemorrhage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Splanchnic vasoconstrictors reduce portal pressure","Splanchnic vasodilators decrease bleeding risk","Endoscopic sclerotherapy causes vessel dilation","Band ligation works by promoting vessel growth","Beta blockers provide immediate haemostasis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe management of acute variceal hemorrhage involves multiple approaches to reduce portal pressure and achieve haemostasis. \u003Cstrong\u003ESplanchnic vasoconstrictors\u003C/strong\u003E like octreotide and terlipressin are first-line pharmacological treatments that reduce portal blood flow and pressure. The suggestion that \u003Cstrong\u003Esplanchnic vasodilators\u003C/strong\u003E would help is incorrect as this would worsen portal pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic sclerotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E and band ligation work by physically obliterating varices - not through \u003Cstrong\u003Evessel dilation\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Epromoting vessel growth\u003C/strong\u003E. While \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta blockers\u003C/strong\u003E are important for preventing primary or secondary haemorrhage, they do not provide immediate control of acute bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of pharmacological therapy (vasoconstrictors) and endoscopic therapy (band ligation or sclerotherapy) provides the best outcomes in acute variceal bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute variceal hemorrhage is treated with endoscopic band ligation or sclerotherapy","Pharmacological therapy for variceal bleeding uses splanchnic vasoconstrictors like octreotide or terlipressin","Management includes both endoscopic and pharmacological approaches to reduce portal pressure"],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808","Edelson J, Basso JE, Rockey DC. Updated strategies in the management of acute variceal haemorrhage. Curr Opin Gastroenterol. 2021 May 1;37(3):167-172. doi: 10.1097/MOG.0000000000000723. PMID: 33769373; PMCID: PMC8691141."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55540"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15341"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55540"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T17:15:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T08:14:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8032"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70077"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":n